  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering policies\n- 40 recommendations that countries are expected to implement\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- Provides international banking standards for detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n4. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establishes regulatory requirements for financial institutions in EU countries\n\n5. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides guidance and support for countries developing anti-money laundering frameworks\n\nMost countries have implemented domestic laws based on these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal control systems\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset seizure, and criminal prosecution.\n\nThese international efforts aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds and integrating them into the legitimate financial system.",
